dance of “transgender” as an umbrella identity in the mid-1990s. Dame-Griff argues that digital communications sparked significant momentum within what would become the transgender movement, but also further cemented existing power structures. Covering both a historical period that is largely neglected within the history of computing, and the poorly understood role of technology in queer and trans social movements, The Two Revolutions offers a new understanding of both revolutions—the internet’s early development and the structures of communication that would take us to today’s tipping point of trans visibility politics. Through a history of how trans people online exploited different digital infrastructures in the early days of the internet to build a community, The Two Revolutions tells a crucial part of trans history itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aOnline social networkszUnited States. 0aTransgender peoplezUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Transgender Studies.2bisacsh  aDigital Humanities.  aInternet history.  aLGBT history.  aMedia archaeology.  aSocial Movements.  aTransgender history.  aTransgender studies.  aWeb history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479818341.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479818341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479818341/original  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishb202